Here's the complete implementation of the functions using the Hexi library's `buffer_adaptor`:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
#include <cstring>

void write_data_to_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, uint32_t value, const void* data, std::size_t length) {
    // Write the integer value first
    buffer.write(reinterpret_cast<const std::byte*>(&value), sizeof(value));

    // Write the byte array
    if (data != nullptr && length > 0) {
        buffer.write(static_cast<const std::byte*>(data), length);
    }
}

void read_data_from_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, uint32_t& value, void* data, std::size_t length) {
    // Read the integer value first
    buffer.read(reinterpret_cast<std::byte*>(&value), sizeof(value));

    // Read the byte array
    if (data != nullptr && length > 0) {
        buffer.read(static_cast<std::byte*>(data), length);
    }
}

struct BufferInfo {
    std::size_t size;
    std::size_t free_space;
};

BufferInfo get_buffer_info(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer) {
    BufferInfo info;
    info.size = buffer.size();           // Total size of the buffer
    info.free_space = buffer.available(); // Available free space
    return info;
}
```

**Explanation:**

1. **`write_data_to_buffer` function:**
   - First writes the 32-bit integer value by converting it to bytes using `reinterpret_cast`
   - Then writes the byte array data if it's not null and has positive length
   - Uses the `buffer.write()` method to write data to the buffer

2. **`read_data_from_buffer` function:**
   - First reads the 32-bit integer value from the buffer
   - Then reads the byte array data if the destination pointer is not null and length is positive
   - Uses the `buffer.read()` method to read data from the buffer

3. **`get_buffer_info` function:**
   - Returns a `BufferInfo` struct containing:
     - `size`: Total size/capacity of the buffer (using `buffer.size()`)
     - `free_space`: Available free space in the buffer (using `buffer.available()`)

**Note:** The exact method names (`size()`, `available()`, `read()`, `write()`) are based on typical buffer adaptor implementations. If the Hexi library uses different method names, you may need to adjust them accordingly (e.g., `capacity()` instead of `size()`, `free()` instead of `available()`, etc.).

